thread.title: James Henry: We’ve clicked, now watch us go
thread.title_full: James Henry: We’ve clicked, now watch us go

title: James Henry: We’ve clicked, now watch us go
text:
Henry continued his good form this season in the wins over Fulham and Huddersfield, which moved Wolves up to ninth in the table. 
And the 26-year-old is keen for the team to keep the momentum going after the international break. 
“We have had two excellent victories, convincing wins where we have also played some good football,” said Henry, who recently signed a new contract. “We have picked up some good form, now unbeaten in four in the league where we have only conceded one goal. That was important, we needed to get back to conceding zeroes or ones. 
“And away from that it has clicked and now we have a little break where we have to stay fit and try and return in the same form when we come back. 
“We can’t rest on our laurels and have to keep performing the way we are.” 
Henry scored a fine free-kick at Craven Cottage and should have notched his third of the season against the Terriers, but missed a close-range header from Dominic Iorfa’s cross. What do you think? Log in and start commenting 
He is keen to get in among the goals this season. 
“There probably could have been another two or three scored by us, myself included,” Henry added. “With that header I just closed my eyes, a natural winger! 
“But, seriously, I apologised to Dom when I came in after. 
“I know the frustration as a winger when you put a really good ball into the box and someone misses. 
“But at least I am getting those chances – I had three or four good ones and hit the target a couple of times and if I can keep doing that the goals will come. 
“And from a team point of view I think it is good now as it looks like the goals can come from anywhere. 
“Benik got a couple on Saturday, which were set up really well and shows what he can do when he gets the opportunities.” 
The club are still coming to terms with Steve Morgan’s shock announcement to sell Wolves and step down as chairman. But Henry said it wasn’t a matter that had an impact on the players, who since the announcement have registered successive wins. James Henry of Wolverhampton Wanderers. 
“We try to leave all that stuff up to the board and the gaffer,” he said. “In a way it hasn’t really got anything to do with us. 
“We are paid to play for this great club and need to keep doing that to the best of our ability and focusing on our own goals – to get into the top six.”
